AB  - This paper examines the industrial determinants of foreign ownership shares in the large private corporate manufacturing sector of India, which has severly restricted and regulated the activities of foreign multinational companies. Using new data on foreign ownership, it finds that overseas investment is concentrated in activities demanding complex technologies, large-scale production and intensive management (which yields high profits). MNCs do not, however, enter marketing-intensive or capital-intensive sectors, or those requiring advanced levels of general skills. This pattern is due partly to the natural monopolistic advantage of MNCs and partly to the heavily regulated economic regime.
