AB  - Maximum balanced growth paths (turnpikes) are compared with 5-year maximum consumption ones and with the actual Jamaican economy, using 8-sector dynamic Leontief data (A,B) for 1957–1966. The economy is shown to reach the turnpikes within one or two periods from several base year endowments, but with a consumption penalty, reducible depending on the assumptions about the final demand trajectories (closures). With the finite horizon, a relatively flexible final demand policy is shown to be superior to fixed closures, at least by the consumption criterion, since advantage can be taken of the ‘lulls’ in demand for a good as capital stock, to consume more of it.
